==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: dissociate
<hw>dis*so"ci*ate</hw> <pr>(d⟦icr⟧s*s⟦omac⟧"sh⟦icr⟧*⟦amac⟧t)</pr>,
<pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Dissociated</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Dissociating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>dissociatus</ets>,
p. p. of <ets>dissociare</ets> to dissociate; <ets>dis-</ets> +
<ets>sociare</ets> to unite, associate, <ets>socius</ets> companion. See
<er>Social</er>.]</ety> <def>To separate from fellowship or union; to
disunite; to disjoin; <as>as, to <ex>dissociate</ex> the particles of a
concrete substance</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Before Wyclif's death in 1384, John of Gaunt had openly
<qex>dissociated</qex> himself from the reformer.</q> <rj><qau>A. W.
Ward.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>dissociated</ent>⟦br⟧
